    32→\begin{abstract}
    33→Compute-in-Memory (CIM) chips for large language model (LLM) inference face a critical bottleneck: ADC area grows exponentially with bit resolution, reaching 24.4\% of total chip area at 7-bit for OPT-125M (NeuroSIM-validated). Prior mixed-precision methods assume that layers with high ADC saturation rates are the most sensitive to bit reduction---but we demonstrate this is fundamentally incorrect. By \emph{measuring} the perplexity change when each layer type's ADC resolution is independently reduced from 7-bit to 6-bit, we find that attention \texttt{q/k/v\_proj} layers ($\approx$100\% saturation) cause only $\Delta$PPL = 0.13 per layer, while \texttt{fc2} layers ($\approx$19\% saturation) cause $\Delta$PPL = 1.41 per layer---an \textbf{11$\times$ inversion}. This counter-intuitive result shows that saturation rate is a poor proxy for ADC bit-reduction sensitivity. Based on measured sensitivities, we formulate an Integer Linear Program (ILP) to optimally allocate ADC bits under area budget constraints. On OPT-125M (100-batch stable evaluation), the ILP achieves 20.5\% ADC area savings (228.4\,mm$^2$ $\to$ 181.5\,mm$^2$) with only $+$2.2 PPL increase, outperforming saturation-guided greedy by 5.2 PPL. Combined with SmoothQuant, 6-bit uniform allocation achieves PPL=305.0---\emph{lower} than the 7-bit CIM baseline (306.4)---while saving 50\% ADC area. All area results are NeuroSIM-validated.
    34→\end{abstract}
    35→
    36→\begin{IEEEkeywords}
    37→Compute-in-Memory, Large Language Models, ADC Sensitivity, Mixed-Precision, ILP, NeuroSIM
    38→\end{IEEEkeywords}
    39→
    40→%────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    41→\section{Introduction}
    42→\label{sec:intro}
    43→
    44→Compute-in-Memory (CIM) architectures~\cite{chi2016prime,shafiee2016isaac} accelerate LLM inference by performing matrix-vector multiplications (MVM) in resistive memory arrays, eliminating weight transfer between DRAM and processing elements. However, the analog-to-digital converters (ADCs) that digitize accumulated column currents grow exponentially in area with bit resolution: NeuroSIM~\cite{chen2018neurosim} reports that ADC occupies 24.4\% of total chip area at 7-bit and 63.9\% at 10-bit for OPT-125M~\cite{zhang2022opt}.
    45→
    46→Mixed-precision ADC allocation---assigning different bit widths to different layers---can reduce ADC area by exploiting the heterogeneity in LLM layer characteristics. Prior work on digital mixed-precision~\cite{dong2019hawq,wang2019haq} uses gradient-based Hessian or hardware-aware sensitivity to guide bit assignment. For CIM, a natural proxy for sensitivity is the \emph{ADC saturation rate}: layers where activations frequently exceed the ADC full-scale range should need more bits, while low-saturation layers can safely use fewer bits.
    47→
    48→\textbf{Our key finding}: this intuition is wrong for CIM ADC allocation. We directly measure $\Delta$PPL when each layer type's ADC resolution is dropped from 7-bit to 6-bit, and find:
    49→\begin{itemize}
    50→  \item \texttt{q/k/v\_proj} (saturation rate $\approx$100\%) $\to$ $\Delta$PPL/layer = \textbf{0.128} (least sensitive)
    51→  \item \texttt{fc2} (saturation rate $\approx$19\%) $\to$ $\Delta$PPL/layer = \textbf{1.413} (most sensitive)
    52→\end{itemize}
    53→
    54→This 11$\times$ inversion between expected sensitivity (from saturation rate) and measured sensitivity is the central insight of this paper. It occurs because CIM ADC saturation clips the output symmetrically, and the model partially compensates through layer normalization and residual connections---high-saturation layers are systematically ``learned around'' by subsequent processing, while layers whose output feeds directly into the residual stream cause larger accuracy degradation.
    55→
    56→Based on measured sensitivities, we formulate optimal ADC allocation as an ILP and validate area/accuracy tradeoffs with NeuroSIM at the circuit level.
    57→
    58→\noindent\textbf{Contributions}:
    59→\begin{enumerate}
    60→  \item \textbf{Discovery and measurement}: Saturation rate is a poor proxy for CIM ADC sensitivity. We measure per-layer-type $\Delta$PPL directly, revealing an 11$\times$ ordering inversion (attn\_qkv least sensitive despite 100\% saturation; fc2 most sensitive despite only 19\% saturation).
    61→  \item \textbf{ILP allocation}: Optimal budget-constrained bit assignment guided by measured (not proxy) sensitivity, with provable optimality for the discrete ADC area model.
    62→  \item \textbf{NeuroSIM-validated results}: 20.5\% ADC area savings at $+$2.2 PPL cost (ILP), outperforming saturation-guided greedy by 5.2 PPL; combined with SmoothQuant, 50\% ADC savings at PPL below the 7-bit CIM baseline.
    63→\end{enumerate}
    64→
    65→%────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    66→\section{Background}
    67→\label{sec:background}
    68→
    69→\subsection{CIM Array Architecture and ADC Bottleneck}
    70→
    71→In a CIM crossbar, weights $\mathbf{W}$ are stored as conductance states. Input vector $\mathbf{x}$ is applied row-wise via DACs; column currents accumulate by Kirchhoff's law and are digitized by ADCs. For an $M$-column subarray with $b$-bit MLSA-type ADC~\cite{chen2018neurosim}:
    72→\begin{equation}
    73→  A_\text{ADC} \propto M \cdot 2^b
    74→  \label{eq:adc_area}
    75→\end{equation}
    76→since the multi-level sense amplifier area scales linearly with \texttt{levelOutput}~$= 2^b$. Across all layers of OPT-125M (73 linear layers, 4 unique shapes), this gives the area sweep in Table~\ref{tab:ppa_sweep}.
    77→
    78→\subsection{Activation Outliers and ADC Saturation}
    79→
    80→LLM activations develop systematic \emph{outlier channels}~\cite{dettmers2022llmint8}: certain feature dimensions consistently carry values far exceeding the median. For CIM with p99-clip calibration (ADC full-scale set to the 99th percentile of calibration MAC outputs), this causes:
    81→\begin{equation}
    82→  s_i = \Pr\bigl[|y_{ij}| > V_\text{FS}\bigr]
    83→  \label{eq:sat_rate}
    84→\end{equation}
    85→where $s_i$ is the saturation rate for layer $i$ and $V_\text{FS}$ is the ADC full-scale. SmoothQuant~\cite{xiao2023smoothquant} migrates activation difficulty to weights to reduce $s_i$. However, as we show, $s_i$ does not reliably predict the accuracy impact of reducing ADC bits.
    86→
    87→\subsection{NeuroSIM Validation Setup}
    88→
    89→NeuroSIM~\cite{chen2018neurosim} takes per-layer weight/input CSV files and network topology, and outputs circuit-level chip area, ADC area, and energy. For LLM FC layers, we require: \texttt{pipeline=false}, \texttt{speedUpDegree=1}, \texttt{synchronous=false}, \texttt{novelMapping=false}. OPT-125M has 4 unique layer shapes; we run NeuroSIM once per unique shape and aggregate by layer count.
    90→
    91→%────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    92→\section{Measuring Per-Layer ADC Sensitivity}
    93→\label{sec:sensitivity}
    94→
    95→\subsection{Measurement Protocol}
    96→
    97→We define the \emph{ADC sensitivity} of layer $i$ as:
    98→\begin{equation}
    99→  \sigma_i = \Delta\text{PPL}\bigl(b_i: 7 \to 6\bigr) = \text{PPL}(\mathbf{b}^{(i)}) - \text{PPL}(\mathbf{b}^\text{ref})
   100→  \label{eq:sensitivity_measured}
   101→\end{equation}
   102→where $\mathbf{b}^\text{ref} = [7, \ldots, 7]$ is the uniform 7-bit assignment and $\mathbf{b}^{(i)}$ drops only layer $i$ (or all layers of the same type) to 6-bit, keeping all others at 7-bit. This is measured directly via CIM forward-pass simulation with per-layer configurable ADC bits.
   103→
   104→We use group-level measurement (all layers of the same type together) for efficiency, yielding 5 measurements instead of 73. The sensitivity measurement uses 4 calibration batches and 10 evaluation batches (512-token sequences, WikiText-2~\cite{merity2017pointer}), using p99-clip ADC calibration. Final PPL evaluation for all allocation configurations uses 100 evaluation batches (~51K tokens) for stable estimates.
   105→
   106→\subsection{Results: Saturation Rate Inverts Sensitivity Order}
   107→
   108→Table~\ref{tab:sensitivity} shows the critical finding. Saturation rate (column 2) ranks \texttt{q/k/v\_proj} and \texttt{fc1} as most problematic at $\approx$100\%. But measured sensitivity (column 4) ranks them \emph{last} at 0.128 and 0.201 $\Delta$PPL per layer respectively. \texttt{fc2} ranks first at 1.413 $\Delta$PPL per layer despite only 19\% saturation---an \textbf{11$\times$ inversion} between attn\_qkv and fc2.
   109→
   110→\begin{table}[t]
   111→\centering
   112→\caption{Measured ADC Sensitivity vs.\ Saturation Rate Proxy (OPT-125M, 7b$\to$6b)}
   113→\label{tab:sensitivity}
   114→\begin{tabular}{lrrr}
   115→\toprule
   116→Layer type & Sat. rate & $\Delta$PPL (all) & $\Delta$PPL/layer \\
   117→\midrule
   118→\texttt{q/k/v\_proj} (36) & $\approx$100\% & +4.62  & \textbf{0.128} \\
   119→\texttt{fc1}         (12) & $\approx$94\%  & +2.42  & \textbf{0.201} \\
   120→\texttt{fc2}         (12) & $\approx$19\%  & +16.95 & \textbf{1.413} \\
   121→\texttt{out\_proj}   (12) & $\approx$4\%   & +10.39 & \textbf{0.866} \\
   122→\texttt{lm\_head}     (1) & $\approx$100\% & +0.70  & \textbf{0.700} \\
   123→\bottomrule
   124→\end{tabular}
   125→\end{table}
   126→
   127→\textbf{Why does this inversion occur?} CIM ADC saturation is deterministic given the activation distribution---the model has already adapted to partially compensate for it through learned representations. Reducing bits on a high-saturation layer changes the \emph{pattern} of saturation but does not necessarily change the model's output much, because residual connections and layer normalization absorb and redistribute quantization noise. In contrast, layers like \texttt{fc2} and \texttt{out\_proj} feed directly into the residual stream without an intervening normalization; quantization noise at these positions has an unmediated effect and is harder to compensate downstream.
   128→
   129→Fig.~\ref{fig:sensitivity} illustrates the inversion: measured $\Delta$PPL per layer vs.\ saturation rate forms an anti-correlated scatter. Layers with the highest saturation (\texttt{q/k/v\_proj}, \texttt{fc1}) are the safest to reduce. Layers with moderate-to-low saturation (\texttt{fc2}, \texttt{out\_proj}) are the most accuracy-critical. Saturation rate is not only imprecise but actively misleading as a sensitivity proxy.
   130→
   131→\begin{figure}[t]
   132→  \centering
   133→  \includegraphics[width=0.9\columnwidth]{fig3_group_sensitivity}
   134→  \caption{Measured group sensitivity (left: $\Delta$PPL/layer when dropping 7b$\to$6b; right: layer count). \texttt{fc2} and \texttt{out\_proj} are up to 11$\times$ more sensitive than \texttt{q/k/v\_proj}, despite having far lower saturation rates.}
   135→  \label{fig:sensitivity}
   136→\end{figure}
