   139→\section{Optimal Mixed-Precision ADC Allocation}
   140→\label{sec:allocation}
   141→
   142→\subsection{Problem Formulation}
   143→
   144→Given $N$ layers with measured per-layer sensitivity $\sigma_i$ (in PPL/bit-reduction) and a target ADC area budget $B$, find the bit assignment $\mathbf{b} = \{b_1, \ldots, b_N\}$:
   145→\begin{equation}
   146→  \min_{\mathbf{b}} \sum_i \max(0,\, b_\text{nom} - b_i) \cdot \sigma_i
   147→  \quad \text{s.t.}\; \sum_i 2^{b_i} \leq B,\; b_i \in \mathcal{B}
   148→  \label{eq:ilp}
   149→\end{equation}
   150→where $b_\text{nom} = 7$ is the nominal bit width, $\mathcal{B} = \{4,5,6,7,8\}$ is the set of allowed bit widths, and the area constraint uses the MLSA model (Eq.~\ref{eq:adc_area}).
   151→
   152→\subsection{ILP Solution}
   153→
   154→We reformulate~(\ref{eq:ilp}) as a binary ILP. For each layer $i$ and each bit choice $b \in \mathcal{B}$, introduce binary variable $x_{i,b}$:
   155→
   156→\begin{equation}
   157→\min_{\{x_{i,b}\}} \sum_i \sum_{b \in \mathcal{B}} \max(0, b_\text{nom} - b) \cdot \sigma_i \cdot x_{i,b}
   158→\label{eq:ilp_obj}
   159→\end{equation}
   160→\begin{equation}
   161→\text{s.t.}\quad \sum_{b \in \mathcal{B}} x_{i,b} = 1 \;\forall i, \quad
   162→\sum_i \sum_{b} 2^b x_{i,b} \leq B, \quad x_{i,b} \in \{0,1\}
   163→\label{eq:ilp_con}
   164→\end{equation}
   165→
   166→The ILP is solved with \texttt{scipy.optimize.milp}. For OPT-125M (73 layers, 5 choices), the problem has 365 binary variables and solves in $<$0.1\,s to proven optimality.
   167→
   168→\subsection{Sensitivity-Guided Greedy Baseline}
   169→
   170→For comparison, we also implement a greedy baseline that reduces bits for layers in ascending sensitivity order:
   171→
   172→\begin{algorithm}[h]
   173→\caption{Sensitivity-Guided Greedy ADC Allocation}
   174→\label{alg:greedy}
   175→\begin{algorithmic}[1]
   176→\STATE $\mathbf{b} \leftarrow [b_\text{nom}] \times N$, compute $\sigma_i$ from measurements
   177→\STATE Sort indices by $\sigma_i$ ascending (least sensitive first)
   178→\WHILE{$\sum_i 2^{b_i} > B$}
   179→  \FOR{$i$ in sorted order}
   180→    \IF{$b_i > \min(\mathcal{B})$ and $\sum_i 2^{b_i} > B$}
   181→      \STATE $b_i \leftarrow \text{next lower choice in } \mathcal{B}$
   182→    \ENDIF
   183→  \ENDFOR
   184→\ENDWHILE
   185→\RETURN $\mathbf{b}$
   186→\end{algorithmic}
   187→\end{algorithm}
   188→
   189→\subsection{Contrast with Saturation-Guided Allocation}
   190→
   191→The previously assumed saturation-guided allocation places \texttt{q/k/v\_proj} as the most protected layers (highest saturation). Our sensitivity-guided ILP instead identifies \texttt{out\_proj} and \texttt{lm\_head} as the layers requiring the most protection. The key operational difference: saturation-guided allocation \emph{keeps} the already-saturating layers at 7-bit and \emph{reduces} the safe layers, whereas sensitivity-guided allocation reveals the safe layers (by saturation) are actually the most fragile (by accuracy impact).
   192→
