   248→At 20.5\% ADC savings (equal area budget), the ILP achieves PPL=308.6 vs.\ Sens-Greedy's 312.5 ($-$3.9 PPL) and Sat-Greedy's 313.8 ($-$5.2 PPL)---a clear advantage of measuring sensitivity rather than relying on the saturation-rate proxy.
   249→
   250→Fig.~\ref{fig:comparison} shows ILP vs.\ Greedy across all budget targets. ILP wins in \textbf{6 of 8 budget points}, with the largest gain at 10\% savings (+5.8 PPL) and 30\% savings (+3.4 PPL). At extreme budgets (5\% and 50\%), greedy achieves comparable or better PPL because the problem becomes less constrained. The sweet spot for ILP advantage is 10--40\% savings---the practical operating range for CIM chip design.
   251→
   252→A remarkable result from Table~\ref{tab:mixed_results}: \textbf{SQ + Uniform-6b achieves PPL=305.0}---\emph{lower} than the 7-bit CIM baseline (306.4)---while using only 114.2\,mm$^2$ ADC area (50\% savings from 228.4\,mm$^2$). This shows that SmoothQuant can sufficiently reduce activation outliers to make 6-bit ADC competitive with 7-bit on accuracy, yielding a ``free'' 50\% ADC area reduction.
