   262→\section{Discussion}
   263→\label{sec:discussion}
   264→
   265→\subsection{Why the Sensitivity Inversion Occurs}
   266→
   267→The saturation model for CIM predicts that high-saturation layers lose accuracy. However, the model's training dynamics have \emph{already} adapted to the presence of activation outliers:
   268→
   269→\begin{enumerate}
   270→  \item \textbf{Systematic vs.\ random error}: High-saturation layers (\texttt{q/k/v\_proj}, \texttt{fc1}) clip the same channels every token (systematic). Subsequent layer normalization~\cite{bondarenko2021understanding} re-normalizes these clipped values, partially restoring dynamic range.
   271→  \item \textbf{Residual stream placement}: \texttt{fc2} (FFN output) and \texttt{out\_proj} (attention output) feed directly into the residual stream, adding to the token representation before any normalization. Noise at these positions propagates unmitigated to the next layer input.
   272→  \item \textbf{Attention redundancy}: The q/k/v computation operates in a high-redundancy space---the attention softmax normalizes across sequence positions, further absorbing quantization noise.
   273→\end{enumerate}
   274→
   275→\subsection{Implications for CIM Chip Design}
   276→
   277→Based on Table~\ref{tab:sensitivity}, we derive the following hardware design guidelines:
   278→
   279→\begin{itemize}
   280→  \item \textbf{Protect first}: \texttt{fc2} at $\geq$7-bit (sensitivity 1.413 PPL/bit/layer --- highest)
   281→  \item \textbf{Also protect}: \texttt{out\_proj} at $\geq$7-bit (sensitivity 0.866 PPL/bit/layer)
   282→  \item \textbf{Reduce safely}: \texttt{q/k/v\_proj} to 6-bit (sensitivity 0.128 PPL/bit/layer)---counterintuitively, these high-saturation layers are the safest to reduce
   283→  \item \textbf{Middle ground}: \texttt{fc1} at 6-7 bit depending on area budget
   284→\end{itemize}
   285→
   286→For OPT-1.3B (scaled from NeuroSIM data, 14.22$\times$ tile count vs.\ 125M), applying the same sensitivity-guided ILP allocation would save 20.5\% of 3,248\,mm$^2$ ADC area, equivalent to saving \textbf{667\,mm$^2$}---larger than the entire OPT-125M chip.
   287→
   288→\textbf{Cross-model generalization}: We ran the sensitivity measurement on OPT-350M (331M params, 24 layers, hidden=1024). At 7-bit CIM, OPT-350M shows severe degradation (PPL: 34.9$\to$872.6), indicating that larger models require higher ADC bits for acceptable operation---consistent with the known outlier-amplification effect. Within the 7-bit regime, the \emph{relative} ordering of layer-type sensitivity holds: \texttt{q/k/v\_proj} remains the least sensitive (smallest $|\Delta$PPL/layer$|$ = 0.033), while \texttt{lm\_head} and \texttt{fc1}/\texttt{fc2} remain more sensitive. This suggests the saturation-sensitivity inversion is a structural property of transformer architectures, not specific to OPT-125M.
   289→
   290→\subsection{Comparison with Saturation-Guided Prior Work}
   291→
   292→Prior CIM quantization work~\cite{xiao2023smoothquant,wei2022outlier} implicitly assumes saturation rate guides accuracy sensitivity. Our measurement shows this assumption fails for CIM ADC allocation. The practical consequence: any CIM design that reduces bits on \texttt{q/k/v\_proj} first (the intuitively ``safe'' choice given low saturation) is making the correct decision by accident---but would make a sub-optimal decision if it tried to protect \texttt{fc2} at the expense of \texttt{q/k/v\_proj}. Saturation-guided allocation would protect \texttt{q/k/v\_proj} (high saturation = protect) and reduce \texttt{fc2} (low saturation = reduce)---exactly backwards relative to measured sensitivity.
   293→
   294→%────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   295→\section{Related Work}
   296→\label{sec:related}
   297→
   298→\textbf{CIM Architectures}: PRIME~\cite{chi2016prime} and ISAAC~\cite{shafiee2016isaac} demonstrated CIM for neural network inference. Applying CIM to LLMs introduces new challenges from activation outliers~\cite{dettmers2022llmint8} and the dominance of FC (not conv) operations.
   299→
   300→\textbf{LLM Quantization}: SmoothQuant~\cite{xiao2023smoothquant} reduces outlier magnitude by per-channel scaling. LLM.int8()~\cite{dettmers2022llmint8} handles outliers via mixed-precision digital computation. GPTQ~\cite{frantar2022gptq} and AWQ~\cite{lin2023awq} address weight-only quantization. None of these model ADC-level sensitivity in CIM hardware.
   301→
   302→\textbf{Mixed-Precision Quantization}: HAWQ~\cite{dong2019hawq} uses Hessian trace to guide bit assignment; HAQ~\cite{wang2019haq} uses hardware-aware reinforcement learning. These approaches are designed for digital accelerators where bit width affects compute precision uniformly. Our work demonstrates that for CIM, the correct sensitivity metric is fundamentally different (and inverted relative to saturation rate).
   303→
   304→\textbf{NeuroSIM}: The NeuroSIM framework~\cite{chen2018neurosim} provides circuit-level CIM benchmarking. We apply it to LLM (FC-only) networks with corrected parameters for non-pipelined synchronous operation.
   305→
   306→%────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   307→\section{Conclusion}
   308→\label{sec:conclusion}
   309→
   310→We present the first direct measurement of per-layer ADC sensitivity for CIM-based LLM inference and demonstrate that ADC saturation rate---the commonly assumed proxy---is actively misleading: \texttt{q/k/v\_proj} layers ($\approx$100\% saturation) are 11$\times$ \emph{less} sensitive to bit reduction than \texttt{fc2} layers ($\approx$19\% saturation). Using measured sensitivities, we solve an ILP to optimally allocate ADC bits under area constraints, achieving 20.5\% ADC area savings (228.4\,mm$^2$ $\to$ 181.5\,mm$^2$, NeuroSIM-validated) with only $+$2.2 PPL degradation on OPT-125M, outperforming saturation-guided greedy by 5.2 PPL. Combined with SmoothQuant, 6-bit uniform allocation achieves PPL=305.0 (below the 7-bit CIM baseline) while saving 50\% ADC area. Our results provide CIM hardware designers with a measurement-grounded methodology: \emph{measure sensitivity directly, not by proxy}, and use ILP rather than saturation-ordered greedy to optimize ADC allocation.
